evidences.sub_surface: North-west White Island Antarctic Specially Protected Area
evidences.masked_sentence: The North-west White Island [MASK] Specially Protected Area comprises a 142 km2 area of coastal shelf ice on the north-west side of White Island in the Ross Archipelago of Antarctica.The site has been designated an Antarctic Specially Protected Area (ASPA 137) because it supports an unusual small breeding population of Weddell seals, which is not only the most southerly known, but which has also been physically isolated from other populations by the advance of the McMurdo and Ross ice shelves.

Amphibole Peak (84°44′S173°26′W﻿ / ﻿84.733°S 173.433°W) is, at 1,660 metres (5,450 ft), the highest peak in the Gabbro Hills, standing 4 nautical miles (7 km) north of Mount Llano, in the Queen Maud Mountains of [MASK].

Pratts Peak is a rock peak in [MASK] located 11 kilometres (6.8 mi) east of Mount Provender in the west part of Shackleton Range.

Hochstetter Peak (Bulgarian: връх Хохщетер, ‘Vrah Hochstetter’ 'vr&h 'hoh-shte-ter) is the partly ice-free bluff rising to over 1000 m in the southeast foothills of Louis-Philippe Plateau on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, [MASK].
Smin Peak (Bulgarian: връх Смин, ‘Vrah Smin’ 'vr&h 'smin) is the partly ice-free peak rising to 850 m in the southeast foothills of Louis-Philippe Plateau on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, [MASK].

Konush Hill (Bulgarian: Конушки хълм, ‘Konushki Halm’ 'ko-nush-ki 'h&lm) is the ice-covered hill rising to 550 m in the north foothills of Louis-Philippe Plateau on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, [MASK].

Tintyava Peak (Bulgarian: връх Тинтява, ‘Vrah Tintyava’ 'vr&h tin'tya-va) is the ice-covered peak rising to 950 m in the north foothills of Louis-Philippe Plateau on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, [MASK].

Ogled Peak (Bulgarian: връх Оглед, ‘Vrah Ogled’ 'vr&h 'o-gled) is the ice-covered peak rising to over 700 m in the north foothills of Louis-Philippe Plateau on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, [MASK].

Hervéou Point (65°4′S64°3′W﻿ / ﻿65.067°S 64.050°W) is a point forming the western extremity of the rocky peninsula between Port Charcot and Salpetriere Bay, on the west side of Booth Island in the Wilhelm Archipelago, [MASK].

Camp Academia (Lager Akademiya 'la-ger a-ka-'de-mi-ya) is a geographical locality in eastern Livingston Island, South Shetland Islands, Antarctica, named for the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences in appreciation of Academy’s contribution to the [MASK] exploration.

Vardim Rocks (Bulgarian: скали Вардим, ‘Skali Vardim’ ska-'li 'var-dim) are a group of rocks situated on the south side of Hell Gates, facing Devils Point in the southwest extremity of Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Gerlovo Beach (Bulgarian: Герловски бряг, ‘Gerlovski Bryag’ 'ger-lov-ski 'bryag) is a beach extending 2 km on the northwest coast of Ioannes Paulus II Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Belchin Rock (Bulgarian: скала Белчин, ‘Skala Belchin’ ska-'la bel-'chin) is a rock off the north coast of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated in Hero Bay 2.2 km (1.4 mi) northeast of Siddins Point and 2 km (1.2 mi) north of Melta Point.

Koynare Rocks (Bulgarian: скали Койнаре, ‘Skali Koynare’ ska-'li koy-'na-re) are a small group of rocks in Hero Bay off the north coast Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated 7.5 km (4.66 mi) northeast of Siddins Point, 5.3 km (3.29 mi) northwest of Bezmer Point, and 1.4 km (0.87 mi) south of Miladinovi Islets.

Ihtiman Hook (Bulgarian: Ихтиманска коса, ‘Ihtimanska Kosa’ ih-ti-'man-ska ko-'sa) is a gravel barrier spit extending 700 m westward from the north coast of Burgas Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
Gerov Pass (Bulgarian: Геров проход, ‘Gerov Prohod’ 'ge-rov 'pro-hod) is a pass of elevation 400 m in Friesland Ridge, Tangra Mountains on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
Zornitsa Cove in Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK], is named after Zornitsa.

Bulgarian Antarctic Institute is the national Antarctic operator of Bulgaria, organizing annual Antarctic campaigns, maintaining the Bulgarian Antarctic base of St. Kliment Ohridski on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands and five times winners of the [MASK] Institute of the Year Award.

Ballester Point (Bulgarian: нос Балестер, ‘Nos Ballester’ 'nos ba-'les-ter) is a point forming the south side of the entrance to Johnsons Dock and the northeast side of the entrance to Española Cove in Hurd Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Lukovit Point (Bulgarian: нос Луковит, ‘Nos Lukovit’ 'nos 'lu-ko-vit) is an ice-free point on the coast of Hero Bay, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] forming the west side of the entrance to Maleshevo Cove.

Valchedram Island (Bulgarian: остров Вълчедръм, ‘Ostrov Valchedram’ 'os-trov 'v&l-che-dr&m) is an ice-free island off the north coast of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] extending 280 m (310 yd) in southeast-northwest direction.
Remetalk Point on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is named after him.
Osogovo Bay in Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is named after Osogovo.

Gerov Pass in Tangra Mountains on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is named after Nayden Gerov.
Nusha Hill (Bulgarian: Нушин хълм, ‘Nushin Halm’ 'nu-shin 'h&lm) is the rocky hill rising to 251 m in southern Hurd Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Copland Peak (71°27′S73°16′W﻿ / ﻿71.450°S 73.267°W) is a peak 3 nautical miles (6 km) northeast of the Mussorgsky Peaks and about 1.2 miles (2 km) south of Mazza Point near the tip of Derocher Peninsula, in the north central area of Beethoven Peninsula, situated in southwest Alexander Island, [MASK].
It was named by the New Zealand [MASK] Place-Names Committee in association with Byrd Glacier.

The Elgar Uplands (69°39′S70°43′W﻿ / ﻿69.650°S 70.717°W) are uplands rising to 1,900 metres (6,200 ft), between Tufts Pass to the north and Sullivan Glacier to the south, in the northern part of Alexander Island, [MASK].
Gerontius Glacier (69°31′S70°34′W﻿ / ﻿69.517°S 70.567°W) is a glacier flowing north from the Elgar Uplands into Tufts Pass in northern Alexander Island, [MASK].

Care Heights (69°25′S70°45′W﻿ / ﻿69.417°S 70.750°W) are a group of mostly ice-covered peaks and ridges, rising to about 1,500 metres (4,900 ft) north of Tufts Pass and forming the southern end of the Rouen Mountains, northern Alexander Island, [MASK].
Tufts Pass (69°25′S70°35′W﻿ / ﻿69.417°S 70.583°W) is a pass extending in an east-west direction between the Rouen Mountains and the Elgar Uplands in the north part of Alexander Island, [MASK].
Remapped from air photos taken by the Ronne [MASK] Research Expedition in 1947–48, by Searle of the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey in 1960.
Tufts Pass (69°25′S70°35′W﻿ / ﻿69.417°S 70.583°W) is a pass extending in an east-west direction between the Rouen Mountains and the Elgar Uplands in the north part of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Serpent Nunatak (69°28′S70°55′W﻿ / ﻿69.467°S 70.917°W) is a nunatak which is seen in the shape of a reverse letter S, rising to about 750 m just west of Tufts Pass lying within the Nichols Snowfield, in the northern portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Podgore Saddle (Bulgarian: седловина Подгоре, ‘Sedlovina Podgore’ se-dlo-vi-'na pod-'go-re) is the ice-covered flat saddle of elevation 2250 m linking Tyree Ridge to Bearskin Ridge on the east side of Sentinel Range in Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK].
Knob Point (77°48′S166°40′E﻿ / ﻿77.800°S 166.667°E) is a rounded coastal point on the west side of Hut Point Peninsula, Ross Island, [MASK].
The feature was visited by Victoria University of Wellington [MASK] Expedition (VUWAE), 1976–77, led by Christopher J. Burgess.

Scuttle Valley (76°38′S161°9′E﻿ / ﻿76.633°S 161.150°E) is a small deglaciated valley with meltwater lakes that lies parallel to and just south of Towle Glacier in the Convoy Range, Victoria Land, [MASK].

The Kinzl Crests (67°5′S66°18′W﻿ / ﻿67.083°S 66.300°W) are three peaks, 2,135 metres (7,000 ft) high, on Pernik Peninsula, Loubet Coast in Graham Land, [MASK], standing 3 nautical miles (6 km) east of Salmon Cove and Lallemand Fjord.

They were mapped from air photos taken by the Falkland Islands and Dependencies Aerial Survey Expedition, 1956–57, and were named by the UK [MASK] Place-Names Committee for Hans Kinzl, an Austrian glaciologist.
McNeile Glacier (63°54′S59°26′W﻿ / ﻿63.900°S 59.433°W) is a glacier flowing northward to the southeast side of Almond Point where it enters Charcot Bay, on the west side of Graham Land, [MASK].
The name, given by the United Kingdom [MASK] Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1963, is derived from the Firth of Tay.
Cape Klovstad (71°39′S170°6′E﻿ / ﻿71.650°S 170.100°E) is a rugged rock point between Colbeck Bay and Protection Cove in the southern part of Robertson Bay, Victoria Land, [MASK].
